Collision Detection

Collision detection is a fundamental component of the BepuPhysics engine, responsible for identifying when objects intersect or are about to intersect. This system combines broad and narrow phase algorithms to efficiently detect collisions and generate appropriate contact constraints for the solver.

For information about shape representation, see Shape System. For details on how the constraints are solved, see Constraint System.

System Overview

The collision detection pipeline in BepuPhysics is divided into two main phases:

  1. Broad Phase: Quickly identifies potential collisions using spatial partitioning structures.
  2. Narrow Phase: Performs precise collision detection on pairs identified by the broad phase and generates contact constraints for the solver.

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/BroadPhase.cs1-473
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhase.cs1-123
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/CollidableOverlapFinder.cs1-39

Collision Detection Pipeline

The collision detection process follows these key steps:

  1. Bounding Box Prediction: Bodies' positions are predicted and bounding boxes are updated
  2. Broad Phase Processing: Spatial trees are refined and queried to find potential overlaps
  3. Overlap Collection: Potential pairs are gathered and dispatched to worker threads
  4. Narrow Phase Processing: Precise collision detection is performed on each pair
  5. Constraint Generation: Contact manifolds are converted into constraints for the solver
  6. Pair Cache Management: Collision pair information is stored for the next frame

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhase.cs180-282
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/BroadPhase.cs209-239
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/CollidableOverlapFinder.cs59-139

Broad Phase

The broad phase rapidly identifies potential collisions using spatial partitioning structures. This avoids the need to perform expensive detailed collision tests between all possible object pairs.

Spatial Trees

BepuPhysics uses two tree structures for spatial partitioning:

  1. ActiveTree: Contains wakeful (moving) bodies
  2. StaticTree: Contains sleeping bodies and static objects

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree.cs11-33
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/BroadPhase.cs34-63

Tree Maintenance

To maintain effective spatial queries, the broad phase periodically:

  1. Refits the trees to account for moving objects
  2. Refines the trees to improve their structure for more efficient queries

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_Refit.cs1-59
  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_Refit2.cs1-118
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/BroadPhase.cs209-239

Overlap Finding

After the trees are updated, the CollidableOverlapFinder queries them to find potential collisions:

  1. Self-overlaps within the active tree (active-active pairs)
  2. Intertree overlaps between active and static trees (active-static pairs)

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_SelfQueries.cs1-157
  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_IntertreeQueries.cs1-156
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/CollidableOverlapFinder.cs105-162

Narrow Phase

The narrow phase takes potential collisions identified by the broad phase and performs precise collision detection to determine if objects are actually touching or intersecting.

Collision Handling

When a potential collision is identified, the narrow phase:

  1. Determines which objects are involved
  2. Sorts the references for consistency (important for warm starting)
  3. Checks if collision detection is allowed via callbacks
  4. Creates collision batches for efficient processing
  5. Generates contact manifolds
  6. Converts contacts to solver constraints

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhase.cs399-473
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhaseConstraintUpdate.cs147-223

Contact Manifolds

Contact manifolds represent the geometric collision information:

  1. Convex manifolds: Up to 4 contact points
  2. Nonconvex manifolds: Up to 8 contact points (for complex shapes)

Each contact includes:

  • Contact position
  • Contact normal
  • Penetration depth
  • Feature ID (for persistent identification)

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhaseConstraintUpdate.cs147-223
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhaseConstraintUpdate.cs234-289

Constraint Generation

The narrow phase converts contact manifolds into solver constraints. For each pair:

  1. Determines the appropriate constraint type based on:
    • Contact count (1-8)
    • Shape type (convex or nonconvex)
    • Body count (one-body or two-body)
  2. Creates or updates the constraint in the solver
  3. Tracks the constraint in the pair cache for future warm starting

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhaseConstraintUpdate.cs252-289
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhasePendingConstraintAdds.cs137-204

Pair Cache

The pair cache maintains information about collision pairs between timesteps, enabling:

  1. Warm starting: Reusing accumulated impulses from the previous frame
  2. Constraint persistence: Maintaining stable constraint references
  3. Feature matching: Associating contact points across frames

Core Structure

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/PairCache.cs102-130
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/PairCache.cs15-32
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/PairCache.cs78-100
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/WorkerPairCache.cs9-50

Freshness Checking

To maintain an accurate pair cache, a "freshness" checking system identifies and removes stale collision pairs:

  1. Each narrow phase update marks encountered pairs as "fresh"
  2. During flushing, a freshness checker identifies unmarked (stale) pairs
  3. Stale pairs are removed from both the pair cache and the solver

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/FreshnessChecker.cs59-137
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/PairCache.cs152-157

Multithreading

BepuPhysics leverages multithreading throughout the collision detection pipeline for better performance on modern hardware:

Parallelization Strategy

  1. Broad Phase: Tree refinement and queries are parallelized
  2. Overlap Testing: Overlap tests are distributed across worker threads
  3. Narrow Phase: Collision detection is batched across worker threads
  4. Constraint Management: Constraint additions and removals are processed in parallel

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_SelfQueriesMT.cs42-118
  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_IntertreeQueriesMT.cs13-107
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhasePreflush.cs110-162

Worker Organization

The collision detection system uses several worker-specific data structures to avoid contention:

  1. OverlapWorkers: Per-thread contexts for narrow phase collision processing
  2. WorkerPendingPairChanges: Thread-local buffers for pending pair cache updates
  3. TaskStack: Distributes work across threads for tree operations

This organization allows for efficient parallel processing without excessive synchronization overhead.

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhase.cs333-380
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/WorkerPairCache.cs9-50
  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_SelfQueriesMT.cs80-107

Performance Optimizations

BepuPhysics implements several optimizations to make collision detection efficient:

  1. Tree refinement policies: Adapts tree improvement efforts based on tree size and quality
  2. SIMD operations: Uses vectorized math for bounding box tests and other operations
  3. Cache-friendly data layout: Optimizes memory access patterns for better performance
  4. Speculative contacts: Generates contacts with a margin to avoid jitter and allow warm starting
  5. Batched constraint processing: Groups similar constraints for better instruction-level parallelism

Sources:

  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/BroadPhase.cs275-327
  • BepuPhysics/Trees/Tree_Refit2.cs145-347
  • BepuUtilities/BoundingBox.cs78-114
  • BepuPhysics/CollisionDetection/NarrowPhase.cs500-534

Summary

The collision detection system in BepuPhysics efficiently identifies and processes object collisions through a multi-stage pipeline:

  1. The broad phase uses spatial trees to quickly filter potential collisions
  2. The overlap finder queries these trees to identify candidate pairs
  3. The narrow phase performs precise collision detection on each pair
  4. Generated contacts are converted to constraints for the solver
  5. The pair cache maintains information between timesteps for warm starting

This architecture balances performance with accuracy through spatial partitioning, multithreading, and careful memory management - resulting in a collision detection system that scales well with simulation complexity.
